OKLAHOMA CITY BOMBING: 168 Days of Remembrance

by KTUL staff

Tue, November 5th 2019 at 9:31 PM
Updated Mon, April 20th 2020 at 10:56 PM
169
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
The Field of Empty Chairs represents the 168 lives lost. (Courtesy of Oklahoma City National Memorial & Museum)

NOTE: This story was originally posted Nov. 4, 2019, and will be updated throughout the 168 Days of Remembrance.

---

TULSA, Okla. (KTUL) - Today, a special countdown is beginning to honor the victims and survivors of the Oklahoma City bombing.

We're exactly 168 days away from the 25th anniversary. The number 168 is significant because it's the number of people who died.

Today, and every day through April, the Oklahoma City National Memorial Museum is remembering one of the victims. They're also remembering the survivors and the lives that changed forever after Timothy McVeigh set off a truck bomb outside the Murrah Federal Building.

Our coverage of the bombing had a lasting effect on all of our Channel 8 family.

We're partnering with the memorial in honoring the victims and survivors of the bombing.

Each day, we'll take a moment to remember the 168 people who died.

On Monday, Nov. 4, we remembered 33-year-old Lucio Aleman Jr., who was a safety engineer with the Federal Highway Administration.

On Tuesday, Nov. 5, we remembered 33-year-old Teresa Antionette Alexander, a wife and mother of three, who had gone alone to the Murrah Federal Building to get a Social Security card for her 8-month-old son Sean.

On Wednesday, Nov. 6, we remembered Richard A. Allen who was a claims representative for the Social Security Administration when he was killed in the bombing.

On Thursday, Nov. 7, we remembered 48-year-old Ted L. Allen, a father of six and an urban planner for U.S. Housing and Urban Development, who was writing state-by-state regulations for homeless housing programs when he was killed in the bombing.

On Friday, Nov. 8, we remembered Baylee Almon, who celebrated her first birthday the day before the terrorist bomb took her life. She was described by family members as having a loving, heart-filled smile.

"An amateur photographer snapped her photo as a firefighter carried her away from the destroyed building. The photo appeared on the front pages of newspapers and magazines worldwide. Of all the thousands of photos taken at the site, the photo of Baylee captured the horror of the bombing and took it straight to the heart of a sorrowful nation," the Oklahoma City National Memorial Museum said.

On Saturday, Nov. 9, we remembered Diane E. Hollingsworth Althouse. She was a program support assistant for the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development when she was killed in the bombing.

On Sunday, Nov. 10, we remembered Rebecca Needham Anderson. She was a giver, and “gave the ultimate gift to mankind” when she collapsed and later died rescuing survivors at the bombed federal building. “She gave her life helping other people. She was safe. She could have stayed home,” her husband, Fred Anderson, said. Rebecca was a practical nurse at Brookwood Nursing Center. At the time of her death, Rebecca’s Children were Hilary Johnson, 15; Gabe Johnson, 18; Rachael Harrold, 12; and Britton Harrold, 10.

On Monday, Nov. 11, we remembered 36-year-old Pamela Cleveland Argo who was a data entry specialist at Presbyterian Hospital. She was the second person positively identified as a fatality in the April 19 explosion. On top of her job as a data entry specialist, she also delivered homebound meals and assisted AIDS foundations and Feed the Children.

On Tuesday, Nov. 12, we remembered 34-year-old Saundra G. Avery of Midwest City. She loved to work with the children at her church, Life Christian Center, where she played in the orchestra and bell choir. She was a development clerk with the Social Security Administration when she was killed in the bombing.

On Wednesday, Nov. 13, we remembered Peter Avillanoza who was a strong supporter of the community. He was a football and baseball coach and taught judo at the YMCA. A native of Honolulu, Avillanoza was a former police officer and firefighter in Honolulu. He had six children and 14 grandchildren.

He became the director of the Office of Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity shortly before the bombing.

On Thursday, Nov. 14, we remembered 68-year-old Calvin Battle. On April 19, Battle and his wife, Peola, went to the Social Security office in the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building to apply for disability assistance because he had recently suffered a stroke.

Peola Battle also died in the explosion.

Calvin Battle had worked as a machinist for Corken International, his daughter, Janet Battle, said. She said her father did not judge people, but was very accepting of everyone he met.

On Friday, Nov. 15, we remembered 51-year-old Peola Battle, wife of Calvin Battle who was also killed in the bombing. Janet Battle, her daughter, described her mother as a “Christian lady” who attended Greater Mount Carmel Baptist Church.

Janet and Calvin Battle raised four daughters.

On Saturday, Nov. 16, we remembered Danielle Nicole Bell, just 15-months-old, she liked the outdoors and birds and she liked to smile.

“She was just like an angel from God,” said her mother, Deniece Bell. “She always had a smile on her face, and she would do whatever she could to bring one to yours.” She was loved by many people, especially her mom and her grandparents and her uncle,” her mother said. “Anyone who knew her will always remember that precious smile, and we’ll all miss her and never forget the love and the smile.”

On Sunday, Nov. 17, we remembered Oleta C. Biddy. Oleta Christine Biddy always had a smile on her face, said her sister-in-law, Doris Jennings. People seemed to love being around her, as shown by the thousand-plus guests who attended her funeral at the First Baptist Church of Tuttle.

“She was just a fabulous person,” Jennings said. “I said when she married my brother that I could have been jealous because my parents thought she was so wonderful, but she was.” Biddy, 54, also enjoyed working in the church nursery. She was a service representative for the Social Security Administration. Her survivors include her husband, Henry, two sisters, and a son and daughter-in-law.

On Monday, Nov. 18, we remembered 25-year-old Shelly Bland, who was an asset forfeiture specialist for the Drug Enforcement Agency and a mother. Her husband, Gary, said she was devoted to her daughter, Jordan Elizabeth.

“One of her greatest qualities was that she was a wonderful mother," Gary said.

Shelly and Gary Bland had been married for less than a year. They were wed on June 3, 1994.

On Tuesday, Nov. 19, we remembered 33-year-old Andrea Yvette Blanton who worked as a secretary at the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

Her husband, Daniel, said, "She also loved children, entertaining them, taking them places and doing things with them."

On Wednesday, Nov. 20, we remembered 61-year-old Olen Burl Bloomer who was a budget assistant for the U.S. Department of Agriculture. He was admired by his staff for his ability to stay cool under pressure and cut through bureaucratic red tape when emergencies arose.

He was an “average man” who enjoyed telling jokes and laughing, said daughter Maureen Bloomer.

On Thursday, Nov. 21, we remembered 40-year-old Sergeant First Class Lola Bolden was working in the U.S. Army Recruiting Battalion when she was killed in the bombing.

The single mother of three had transferred from Colorado to Oklahoma in January that year. Her son Ricky described her as kind and funny.

On Friday, Nov. 22, we remembered 51-year-old James E. Boles, a husband and father of two, had worked in four states for the U.S. Department of Agriculture before taking over the reins of the Oklahoma City office in 1991.

Boles served in the Army from 1964-68 as a noncommissioned officer in charge of the 793rd military police battalion in Bayreuth, Germany.

On Saturday, Nov. 23, we remembered 28-year-old Mark A. Bolte who received a bachelor’s degree in civil engineering from the University of Arkansas and went to Austin to finish training as a highway engineer for the Federal Highway Administration.

He was promoted in late 1994 to area engineer and when he heard of an opening for an environmental specialist in Oklahoma, he took the position.

Bolte loved hockey and the Razorbacks.

On Sunday, Nov. 24, we remembered Casandra Kay Booker. She “was a sweet, caring person,” said her mother, Gloria Graves. “She would reach out to everybody and always be there for you when you needed her.” Platt College has established an annual scholarship in her name and many have donated money toward a trust fund for her four children. Booker, 25, was applying for Social Security cards for two of her children at the time of the bombing.

On Monday, Nov. 25, we remembered 53-year-old Carol Louise Bowers who was an operations supervisor for the Social Security Administration.

Relatives said Bowers was the kind of person who bubbled and spread joy wherever she went.

On Tuesday, Nov. 26, we remembered 3-year-old Peachlyn Bradley. Bradley’s great-grandmother, Mary Hill, said the girl “was the laugh of everything.”

Peachlyn died in the bombing along with her grandmother, Cheryl Bradley Hammon, and her 3-month-old brother, Gabreon Bruce. The family, including Peachlyn’s mother, Daina Bradley, 20, had gone to get a Social Security card for Gabreon.

On Wednesday, Nov. 27, we remembered 41-year-old Woodrow Clifford "Woody" Brady who was a publisher of children's books. Brady was a customer at the Federal Employees Credit Union on the third floor of the building when the blast occurred.

On Thursday, Nov. 28, we remembered 26-year-old Cynthia Lynn (Campbell) Brown who worked as a special agent for the Secret Service on the ninth floor of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.

On Friday, Nov. 29, we remembered 43-year-old Paul Gregory Beatty Broxterman who was working as a criminal investigator through the inspector general's office when the bombing occurred.

Broxterman served in the Navy from 1971 to 1977 and spent part of that time in Vietnam as a radio man on the USS Enterprise.

On Saturday, Nov. 30, we remembered 3-month-old Gabreon DeShawn Lee Bruce who was taken to the Social Security office by his mother, Daina Bradley, to get a card for him when the bombing occurred.

His great-grandmother, Mary Hill, said Gabreon was a "lovable" baby. Gabreon's grandmother, Cheryl Bradley Hammon, was killed in the blast, and Daina and Gareon's aunt Felicia were injured.

On Sunday, Dec. 1, we remembered 29-year-old Kimberly Ruth Burgess who moved to Oklahoma City, where she lived with her husband, Senior Airman Damon W. Burgess, at Tinker Air Force Base.

Kimberly was described as a loving and caring wife.

On Monday, Dec. 2, we remembered 47-year-old David Neil Burkett. He traveled across the United States working with Indian tribes as a leader for the reorganization of the Native American Department. He also worked as a financial analyst for community development in the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

On Tuesday, Dec. 3, we remembered 62-year-old Donald Earl Burns Sr. who worked as a construction analyst for the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

He was a former football coach at Douglass High School and taught woodworking for many years. As a coach at Douglass, Burns guided the lives of such future stars as Albert Chandler and Raymond Hamilton, both of whom played for the Oklahoma Sooners and the New England Patriots.

On Wednesday, Dec. 4, we remembered 32-year-old Karen Gist Carr who was an advertising assistant for the Army recruiting office.

In addition to her full-time job, she was an aerobics instructor at the Downtown YMCA and at Rose State College. She also was a member of the Mid-Del Toastmasters Club. Carr and her husband, Gregory Carr, had just celebrated their eighth anniversary eight days before she was killed.

On Thursday, Dec. 5, we remembered 44-year-old Michael Carrillo.

After spending four years in the Navy, Carrillo enlisted and served four more years in the Army. That was before settling into a career he enjoyed with the Federal Highway Administration. Carrillo and his three teenage children had lived in Oklahoma City for the last two years, building a life together after losing a loving wife and mother two years previous after an unsuccessful kidney transplant when he died.

On Friday, Dec. 6, we remembered 3-year-old Zackary Taylor Chavez. Zackary had been cared for by workers at the day-care center inside the Murrah building his entire life.

His great-grandfather remembered giving him quarters. “When you would give him a quarter, he would always take it to his mom. He was a cute little guy,” said Cereaco Hernandez. “You would try to give him a dollar, and he would say ‘No, no – give me a quarter.’”

On Saturday, Dec. 7, we remembered 51-year-old Robert N. Chipman who had been with the Oklahoma Water Resources Board as a financial analyst for six months.

A "prince of guys," is how Edmond Memorial High School Principal Larry Maxwell described Chipman.

“He was a great guy to be around and work with,” Maxwell said. “It’s a shame that has to happen to someone like that, (someone who) has such a positive outlook on life.”

On Sunday, Dec. 8, we remembered 39-year-old Kimberly Kay Clark who was a legal assistant for the Housing and Urban Development Department and a petty officer first class in the U.S. Naval Reserve.

Clark thrived on adventure and enjoyed long-distance biking and traveling.

On Monday, Dec. 9, we remembered Dr. Margaret L. "Peggy" Clark who was a veterinary medical officer with the Department of Agriculture and only stopped at her office in the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building for some last-minute business April 19.

Peggy had three daughters – Rosslyn, 16, Blayne, 13, and Chelsea, 6. She was active in the Future Farmers of America and 4-H clubs at Chickasha High School, where her oldest daughter attended classes.

Before joining the Agriculture Department in 1994, Clark worked as track veterinarian at Blue Ribbon Downs.

On Tuesday, Dec. 10, we remembered 2-year-old Anthony Christopher Cooper II.

"From his playful antics to his beautiful singing voice to his handsome face, he was a happy child," Anthony's father, Anthony Cooper, said.

Anthony's mother, 24-year-old Dana Cooper, was the new director of the America’s Kids day care center in the federal building. She also died in the bombing.

On Wednesday, Dec. 11, we remembered 6-month-old Antonio Ansara Cooper Jr. was just learning to crawl and say “Da-Da.”

Young Cooper also liked to be thrown up in the air and watch his mother, Renee Cooper, dance. He had attended America’s Kids day care center since December.

On Thursday, Dec. 12, we remembered 24-year-old Dana LeAnne Cooper who was the new director for America's Kids day care center in the Murrah Building.

Dana's husband, Anthony, said his wife loved all children. “She was the most beautiful person I ever met. Everything she did, she did for the children,” Cooper said.

Their 2-year-old son, Anthony Christopher Cooper II, also died in the bombing.

On Friday, Dec. 13, we remembered 46-year-old Harley Richard Cottingham who was a special agent with the Department of Defense Investigative Service.

Cottingham served in the U.S. Navy from 1969-1973. He continued his career in government service in 1980 when he joined the Veterans Administration as a Veterans Outreach Counselor.

To friends and co-workers, he was a “positive person who was always happy and who was able to raise the spirits of co-workers when they were down.”

On Saturday, Dec. 14, we remembered 33-year-old Kim R. Cousins of Midwest City who was an active member of South Lindsay Baptist Church, where she was a second-grade Sunday school teacher.

Children, especially Cousins' 9-year-old son Corey, were a big part of her life.

On Sunday, Dec. 15, we remembered 5-year-old Aaron Coverdale.

"He was a typical big brother, picking up Elijah’s toys and setting out his grandmother’s glasses and keys each day so she wouldn’t forget them."

On Monday, Dec. 16, we remembered 2-year-old Elijah S. Coverdale.

He was attending America's Kids daycare when he was killed in the bombing.

On Tuesday, Dec. 17, we remembered 14-month-old Jaci Rae Coyne.

Jaci, the only child of Scott and Sharon Coyne, loved the "Itsy Bitsy Spider" song. Her mother sang that song to her from the day she was born until the day she died.

On Wednesday, Dec. 18, we remembered 60-year-old Katherine "Kathy" Louise Cregan. She was a widow devoted to her three sons, William, Regis, and Christopher; her two grandsons, Sean and Jonathan; and her three granddaughters, Rachel, Kari, and Michelle.

Katherine worked as a claims representative for the Social Security Administration for 13 years.

On Thursday, Dec. 19, we remembered 55-year-old Richard "Dick" Cummins who was a senior investigator for the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Cummins worked to ensure that animal breeders, dealers, and exhibitors complied with the standards of humane care and treatment outlined in the Animal Welfare Act.

He was recognized in 1990 for his work on the Midwest Stolen Dog Task Force, which helped curb the theft of pets for sale to research institutions.

Cummins worked in Henryetta and Durant as an animal health technician in the 1980s before joining the Oklahoma City office in 1987.

For Friday, Dec. 20, we remember 44-year-old Steven Douglas Curry who was on the job as a building mechanical inspector for the General Services Administration when the blast hit.

Curry was very active in Calvary Free Will Baptist Church, including serving as a deacon and as a coach of a church basketball team. He had lived in Norman since 1974 and served in the Navy from 1970-74.

He married Kathleen Williams on March 8, 1974, in Norman. The couple had a son and a daughter.

On Saturday, Dec. 21, we remembered 42-year-old Brenda Faye Daniels. She was a teacher at America’s Kids childcare center on the second floor of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. Originally from Wichita Falls, Texas, Daniels spent most of her life working at childcare centers. However, she had worked at America’s Kids less than a year. “ The focus of her life was kids. My mother loved kids,” said her daughter, Chastity Pope of Dallas. Daniels lived in Oklahoma City for 13 years.

On Sunday, Dec. 22, we remembered 29-year-old Sergeant Benjamin LaRanzo Davis of Edmond, Okla. Sergeant Davis was an operations clerk for the U.S. Marine Corps Recruiting Station when he was killed in the bombing. He was a good kid, a U.S. Marine comrade said. “He was always motivated. Even when he answered the telephone,” a Marine at an Oklahoma City recruiting substation said.

On Monday, Dec. 23, we remember 38-year-old Diana Lynne Day, who was the mother of Justin, 11 at the time, was a Housing and Urban Development program assistant. She and her son lived with her parents, Bill Sr. and Frankie Day.

On Tuesday, Dec. 24, we remember 44-year-old Peter L. DeMaster, who was a special agent in the Oklahoma City Investigative Field Office of the Department of Defense Investigative Service.

He and his wife, Kay Barry-DeMaster, were to celebrate their 13th wedding anniversary April 24.

He was described by one friend as "the kind of man you want your sons to grow up to be like."

On Wednesday, Dec. 25, we remembered 49-year-old Castine Brooks Hearn Deveroux, who worked for Housing and Urban Development for seven years.

Her prayer partner, Louise Peters, said Deveroux's comments were always touching and encouraging.

"She was a very lovely, devoted church member," Peters said.

On Thursday, Dec. 26, we remembered 8-month-old Tylor Santoi Eaves.

“He was a happy baby,” his grandmother, Gloria Eaves recalled. “He was bossy and spoiled because he liked attention. He wanted to be able to see you all the time.”

On Friday, Dec. 27, we remembered 4-year-old Ashley Megan Eckles, who had gone with her grandparents, Luther and LaRue Treanor, to the social security office on the ground floor of the Murrah building.

Her grandfather was to retire in May and had a 9:15 a.m. appointment at the social security office. They arrived a little early and were in the building when the bomb exploded at 9:02 a.m.

"Ashley was a happy child who knew no strangers. She had a big heart," said Eckles' aunt, Lois Treanor.

On Saturday, Dec. 28, we remembered 37-year-old Susan Jane Ferrell, who was an attorney for U.S. Housing and Urban Development.

Cats, traveling, people and dancing were four of Ferrell's loves.

"Susan had an incredible passion for dancing." said her mother, Sally Ferrell.

On Sunday, Dec. 29, we remembered 48-year-old Carrol June "Chip" Field, who was the lead support person in the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency's Oklahoma City office.

Field was honored with the DEA Administrator's Award for Distinguished Service in 1994.

On Monday, Dec. 30, we remembered 44-year-old Kathy A. Finley who worked at the Federal Employees Credit Union as a teller and had served as the credit union’s vice president for 10 years. She was born and raised in Oklahoma City.

On Tuesday, Dec. 31, we remembered 45-year-old Judy J. (Froh) Fisher who had three children and a stepdaughter and worked for Housing and Urban Development. She attended Community Bible Church and was involved in a prayer chain group.

On Wednesday, Jan. 1, we remembered 43-year-old Linda Louise Florence who was a mother and a secretary for the U.S. Housing and Urban Development Department.

Florence and her husband, David, had been married for 16 years. With a love of traveling, Florence especially enjoyed going to the lake. She also loved reading and teaching her son, John David.

On Thursday, Jan. 2, we remembered 64-year-old Don Fritzler who was checking on his retirement benefits with his wife, Mary Anne Fritzler, at the social security office when the bomb went off.

Don was a well-known church architect who worked in the Southwest. “I really can’t go anywhere in Oklahoma or Texas that I don’t see a memorial to Don,” said Mike Bass of his friend’s work. Indeed, architecture was Don’s job and his hobby.

The Fritzlers were members of Quail Springs Baptist Church, a church Don designed and at which Mary Anne taught Sunday school. Just weeks before the bombing, the couple learned they were expecting their first grandchild.

On Friday, Jan. 3, we remembered 57-year-old Mary Anne Fritzler who was at the social security office with her husband, Don Fritzler, when the bomb went off.

Mary Anne had taught high school in the Oklahoma City and Midwest City-Del City school districts for 14 years. She attended Southeast High School in Oklahoma City and OU, where she received a bachelor’s degree in business education. In 1982, Mary Anne joined her husband at Fritzler & Associates, where the two worked side by side.

On Saturday, Jan. 4, we remembered 1-year-old Tevin D'Aundrae Garrett.

He was a very happy baby who loved to dance, ride his yellow Lion King bike and slide down his red and blue slide.

On Sunday, Jan. 5, we remembered 61-year-old Laura Jane Garrison who was an admissions clerk at Oklahoma Memorial Hospital and was planning to retire in July.

Garrison was preparing retirement papers at the Social Security office when the bombing occurred.

“She was a quiet sister, devoted to her job and her family,” said her brother, Samuel L. Washington.

On Monday, Jan. 6, we remembered 32-year-old Jamie Genzer who was a loan officer for the Federal Employees Credit Union.

She was also on the board of directors of the America’s Kids Day Care in the Murrah Building. She is survived by her two children, Kyle and Krista Genzer.

On Tuesday, Jan. 7, we remembered 28-year-old Sheila R. Gigger-Driver and her unborn baby Gregory N. Driver II. Sheila was a student at Langston University and was making a deposit at the Federal Employee Credit Union in the federal building at the time of the explosion.

On Wednesday, Jan. 8 we remembered 54-year-old Margaret Betterton Goodson who was a claims representative with the Social Security Administration, working with the disabled because she “wanted to help people.” She had spent nearly 20 years with the federal government.

Whether cruising the countryside as a member of the Happy Bottoms Motorcycle Club or planting trees or watching birds – especially blue jays – Margaret thrived outdoors.

On Thursday, Jan. 9 we remembered 6-month-old Kevin "Lee" Gottshall II who had known nothing but love, a full belly, a dry bottom and many good times, his parents said.

Whether he was pulling down his curtains, running over his puppy with his walker or spitting green beans at his mother, all he had to do was smile and his parents’ hearts would melt.

He was curious and enjoyed seeing new people and things, and he was always happy and laughing. Lee had six teeth and would show them to everyone who would look. “We tried to do everything for him, but he gave more happiness in his short time with us than we ever thought possible,” his parents said in a prepared statement.

On Friday, Jan. 10 we remembered 55-year-old Ethel Griffin who was a claims representative for the Social Security Administration.

An Edmond resident since 1976, Ethel Griffin and her husband, Bruce, a design engineer in Guthrie, were married 26 years.

On Saturday, Jan. 11 we remembered 59-year-old J. Colleen Guiles who was an underwriter for the Housing and Urban Development Department.

Guiles had been a real estate broker in south Oklahoma City.

On Sunday, Jan. 12 we remembered 28-year-old Captain Randolph A. Guzman USMC who moved to Oklahoma City in July 1993 to oversee the recruiting station.

Rescue workers digging through the ruins of the bombed-out federal building found Marine Capt. Guzman encased in rubble, but still seated behind his desk at the Marine Corps recruiting station.

"He was real nice, personable and got along with everyone," said a friend and fellow recruiter.

On Monday, Jan. 13, we remembered Cheryl E. Hammon who was at the Social Security office obtaining a social security card for her grandson when she was killed in the bombing.

On Tuesday, Jan. 14, we remembered 55-year-old Ronald Vernon Harding Sr. who was a claims representative for the Social Security Administration.

He also was an accomplished musician who played five instruments – clarinet, saxophone, flute, violin, and cello. He had also been a member of the Earl Pittman All-Stars jazz band for more than 10 years.

On Wednesday, Jan 15, we remembered 52-year-old Thomas Lynn Hawthorne Sr. who was at the Social Security office helping a retired United Rubber Workers union member clear up a problem with the retiree's federal benefits when the bomb exploded.

In a way, that made it easier," Thomas Hawthorne Jr. said, "because if he had to die now, at least he died as he lived."

On Thursday, Jan. 16, we remembered 44-year-old Doris "Adele" Higginbottom who worked as a Department of Agriculture purchasing agent.

She was active in women’s issues and was manager of the Oklahoma City USDA’s Federal Women’s Program.

Higginbottom joined the U.S. Department of Agriculture as a typist in 1978 and earned a bachelor’s degree in English four years later. After brief periods at the Federal Aviation Administration and the San Antonio Express News, Higginbottom rejoined the USDA in 1980.

For Friday, Jan. 17, we remember 27-year-old Anita Christine Hightower who was a secretary for the Job Corps in an office across the street from the federal building. She had two daughters.

On Saturday, Jan. 18, we remembered 54-year-old Thompson Eugene (Gene) Hodges Jr. who was a supervisor for the Housing and Urban Development Department.

Hodges was married to Deb Doges and had four children.

On Sunday, Jan. 19, we remembered 37-year-old Peggy Louise Holland who was a computer specialist for the Army Recruiting Battalion in Oklahoma City.

Holland gave much of her time to children at Knob Hill Baptist Church as a Sunday school teacher.

On Monday, Jan. 20, we remembered 53-year-old Linda Coleen Housley who worked as a loan officer in the Federal Employees Credit Union.

A graduate of Putnam City High School, Housley lived in the Oklahoma City area most of her life. She attended Highland Baptist Church in Moore. Her husband’s name was Gary and she had three children and two stepchildren.

On Tuesday, Jan. 21, we remembered 45-year-old Dr. George Michael Howard, DVM who worked at the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

On Wednesday, Jan. 22, we remembered 34-year-old Wanda Lee Howell who was a new teacher at the America's Kids day-care center.

Just three weeks before the April 19 bombing, Howell began teaching children in the America’s Kids day-care center in the Alfred P. Murrah Building. Howell had two daughters Tashanna, 14, and Latasha, 10.

On Thursday, Jan. 23, we remembered 37-year-old Robbin Ann Huff and her unborn baby Amber Denise Huff.

Robin and her husband Ronald were expecting their first child, a girl to be named Amber Denise, in June 1995.

"She always wanted kids," said Robbin's sister Richeal Thatcher.

On Friday, Jan. 24, we remembered Dr. Charles E. Hurlburt who was checking on retirement benefits at the Social Security Administration office when he was killed in the bombing.

On Saturday, Jan. 25, we remembered Jean Nutting Hurlburt who went to the Social Security Administration office with her husband, Dr. Charles Hurlburt, to follow up on paperwork.

On Sunday, Jan. 26, we remembered 42-year-old Paul D. Ice who was one of the first special agents assigned to the U.S. Customs Service Oklahoma City office seven years before the bombing.

“The death of a member of the Customs family is always a sad occasion,” said John Hensley, special agent in charge. “The death of Senior Special Agent Ice is especially tragic under the circumstances.”

On Monday, Jan. 27, we remembered 32-year-old Christi Yolanda Jenkins who was a teller at the Federal Employees Credit Union, where she had worked for nine years.

She taught Sunday school, was a greeter at her church and was active in the ladies’ ministry to sick people. She was also a mother of four and a loving wife.

On Tuesday, Jan. 28, we remembered 62-year-old Norma "Jean" Johnson who was an executive secretary for the Defense Investigative Services since June 1989.

She and her husband, Carlos Johnson, had four children, five grandchildren, and three great-grandchildren.

On Wednesday, Jan. 29, we remembered 59-year-old Raymond "Lee" Johnson who was working as a volunteer in the Social Security office with the Older Native American Program.

He was a former council member and a past member of the Oklahoma Indian Education Association and held memberships in the National Indian Education Association and the National Congress of American Indians. He served in both the U.S. Air Force and U.S. Army and was a member of the 45th Infantry Division of the National Guard.

On Thursday, Jan. 30, we remembered 46-year-old Larry James Jones who was a computer program specialist for the Federal Highway Administration and was a part-time professor at the University of Central Oklahoma.

He entered the Air Force at age 18 and served in Vietnam and served 20 years in the military.

On Friday, Jan. 31, we remembered 54-year-old Alvin J. Justes who was a regular customer at the Federal Employees Credit Union.

He served time in the military during the Vietnam War.

On Saturday, Feb. 1, we remembered 18-month-old Blake Ryan Kennedy who attended America's Kids day care since he was 6-weeks-old after his mother, Laura, returned to work in the Health and Human Services office in the federal building.

“He loved it. He couldn’t wait to get there. He didn’t know a stranger. He was always happy. He was always smiling. He was the perfect child,” his father, Steve Kennedy, said.

On Sunday, Feb 2, we remembered 50-year-old Carole Sue Khalil who was an export document examiner for the U.S. Department of Agriculture.

She was noted for her eye for detail and her ability to catch minute mistakes.

On Monday, Feb. 3, we remembered 33-year-old Valerie Jo Koelsch who was the Federal Employees Credit Union’s marketing director.

She attended St. Patrick Catholic Church, where she was involved in many of the church’s ministries. In 1993, she went to World Youth Day in Denver to see the pope.

On Tuesday, Feb. 4, we remembered 57-year-old Ann Kreymborg who was an automation clerk for the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development when she was killed in the bombing.

For Wednesday, Feb. 5, we remember 35-year-old Rona Linn Kuehner-Chafey who had worked for the Cleveland County Sheriff's Office as a dispatcher before being assigned duty as a secretary in the Federal Building.

Chafey was a graduate of Bethany High School and had attended Oklahoma City Community College and Rose State College. She was married and had two children.

On Thursday, Feb. 6, we remembered 41-year-old Teresa Lea Taylor Lauderdale who was a realty specialist with the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

She loved people and people loved her, her family said. Lauderdale, of Shawnee, had a selfless habit of placing the needs of others above her own and diligently worked to raise funds for worthy causes sponsored by the Federal Women’s Program.

Described as a dedicated mother, Lauderdale taught her sons, compassion, trust, thoughtfulness, integrity and, most of all, love. Lauderdale had worked in the Oklahoma City HUD office for 13 years.

On Friday, Feb. 7, we remembered 39-year-old Mary Leasure-Rentie who had worked for the Department of Housing and Urban Development on the seventh floor of the federal building. She had worked for HUD for about six years.

She was also a wife and mother of two.

On Saturday, Feb. 8, we remembered 47-year-old Kathy Cagle Leinen. After 13 years as a collection officer with the Federal Employees Credit Union, Catherine Mary “Kathy” Leinen, was looking forward to the day she could retire. Retirement would mean more time to travel and to camp, which she loved. She also enjoyed working on crafts. Her family said she was the light of their lives.

For Sunday, Feb. 9, we remember 26-year-old Carrie Ann Lenz and her unborn son Michael James Lenz III.

Lenz was a contract employee of DynCorp, and was assigned with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in Oklahoma City.

For Monday, Feb. 10, we remember 51-year-old Donald Ray Leonard. After retiring this year, Secret Service agent Donald Ray Leonard planned to travel and play more golf with his sons. He also loved his career in law enforcement. During his 20 years with the Secret Service, Leonard was responsible for protecting seven U.S. presidents and various political candidates and dignitaries. He received numerous awards for his service.

For Tuesday, Feb. 11, we remember 21-year-old LaKesha Richardson Levy. She was intelligent and a budding comedian. Karen Johnson of New Orleans said her niece was focusing on her medical-related job aspirations, but she had a wonderful sense of humor and could easily have excelled as a comic. In one of their last telephone conversations, Johnson said Levy mentioned she had dreamed she was a stand-up comedian. Johnson said her niece’s dream came as no surprise since she always kept the family laughing.

On Wednesday, Feb. 12, we remembered 2-year-old Dominique Ravae (Johnson) -- London who was attending America's Kids Daycare when he was killed in the bombing.

"Everyone was crazy about Dominique. He was justy my baby. He had you laughing. All the kids were drawn to him. He was smart. He really was. We just have so many good memories of him," his grandmother, Ernestine Looney said.

On Thursday, Feb. 13, we remembered 60-year-old Rheta Bender Long who joined the USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service in 1982 as a program clerk.

"She really didn't have hobbies. She was just really involved in her family and her church," said Janna Evans, U.S. Department of Agriculture spokeswoman.

On Friday, Feb. 14, we remembered 48-year-old Michael L. Loudenslager who was employed as planner/estimator on the first floor of the Murrah building in the area of General Services Administration.

He was also an Oklahoma County Reserve Sheriff (Mounted Patrol), a member of the U.S. Marshall Posse and a Mason and Shriner.

On Saturday, Feb. 15, we remembered 43-year-old Aurelia Donna Luster who had gone to the Murrah building with her husband to apply for Social Security disability funding.

Aurelia and her husband left behind six children after dying in the bomb blast.

“They were a real loving family,” family friend and neighbor, Vern Epperson said. “I don’t think you’d find a more loving couple toward each other and their family. It was truly special. From the smallest children on up, it was just incredible love.”

For Sunday, Feb. 16, we remember 45-year-old Robert Lee Luster Jr. who went to the Murrah building with his wife to apply for Social Security disability funding.

“Their love was just unbelievable,” said family friend and neighbor Vern Epperson.

On Monday, Feb. 17, we remembered 50-year-old Mickey B. Maroney. He was a Secret Service agent, was born in Wichita Falls, Texas. He played defensive end for the University of Arkansas Razorbacks during the football team’s 1964 national championship season and during 1965 and 1966. He had spent nearly half his life – 24 years – working for the government. Maroney was at work when the blast hit.

On Tuesday, Feb. 18, we remembered 34-year-old James K. Martin who was a civil engineer for the Federal Highway Administration.

Quiet and introverted, Martin found friendship in the people he worked with. He also was kind, considerate and warm-hearted.

On Wednesday, Feb. 19, we remembered 35-year-old Rev. Gilberto X. Martinez who was a minister and member of the Oklahoma District Assemblies of God.

He was also a teacher in the Oklahoma city public school system.

Martinez and his wife, Martha, had two sons and three daughters.

On Thursday, Feb. 20, we remembered 53-year-old James A. McCarthy II who worked for the U.S. Housing and Urban Development Department.

McCarthy was transferred to Oklahoma City just four months before the bombing.

On Friday, Feb. 21, we remembered 36-year-old Kenneth Glenn McCullough who was an agent for the Drug Enforcement Agency for five years.

McCullough also served in the Army from 1980-86, then worked for the Department of Defense from 1986 until he went to work for the DEA.

On Saturday, Feb. 22, we remembered 47-year-old Betsy J. (Beebe) McGonnell who worked in single family loan management for the department of Housing and Urban Development.

McGonnell was an active member at St. Michael's, she served her church in a variety of ways, including lending her voice to the choir.

On Sunday, Feb. 23, we remembered 47-year-old Linda Gayle McKinney who was an office manager for the Secret Service on the ninth floor of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building

McKinney was "one of those very special people that God puts on earth, said her husband, Dan. "She was outgoing and friendly and never met anyone she didn't like."

On Monday, Feb. 24, we remembered 19-year-old Cartney Jean McRaven. Airman 1st Class McRaven had returned from a four-month deployment in Haiti two weeks before the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. Four days before the bombing, on April 15, she married Senior Airman Anthony Shane McRaven. The couple were planning a large formal wedding in December. On the morning of April 19, McRaven was in the Social Security office at the Murrah building, reporting her name change. McRaven was a native of Watertown, SD. She was a member of the 3rd Combat Communications Group, 32nd Combat Communications Squadron. She and her husband were both stationed at Tinker Air Force Base. The couple spent much of their spare time helping in a local Salvation Army soup kitchen. “We stand back in tears and disbelief and ask, ‘Why?’” said a press release issued by her unit.

On Tuesday, Feb. 25, we remembered Claude Medearis. After serving as a U.S. Customs agent along the Mexican border between Eagle Pass and Del Rio, Texas, Senior Special Agent Claude Medearis moved to the Oklahoma City office in 1992. Medearis, of Norman, had recently been promoted to senior special agent in charge of the Oklahoma City office. His daughter was Catherine Alaniz, whose husband was killed in the Persian Gulf War. The family requested donations be made through a foundation that assisted families of customs agents killed or injured in the line of duty.

On Wednesday, Feb. 26 we remembered 43-year-old Claudette (Duke) Meek who was vice president of financial services at the Federal Employees Credit Union.

She had been a Federal Employee Credit Union employee for more than 13 years, Meek also had worked as a loan officer and a head teller.

On Thursday, Feb. 27 we remembered 23-year-old Frankie Ann Merrell who was a teller at the Federal Employees Credit Union for three years.

If any of her friends or their families needed help, Merrell was there. “She would go out of her way to help them,” a friend said.

On Friday, Feb. 28 we remembered 27-year-old Derwin W. Miller who was a claims examiner in the Social Security Administration.

A family friend said Miller and his family are well-known and respected members of the small community.

Miller is survived by a daughter, his parents, two brothers and a sister.

On Saturday, Feb. 28 we remembered 64-year-old Eula Leigh Mitchell who was an employee of Manhattan Cleaners and a Sunday school teacher in her church.

Joe Mitchell of Oklahoma City had just a few incidental questions for his wife, Eula, to complete his application for Social Security retirement benefits. But he never made it to the reception area of the Social Security offices in the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building to ask her. The explosion separated them.

Eula loved animals and especially the birds around her home. Her family described her as a friend to many, particularly the elderly friends that she loved to take care of and shop for. Her husband of 26 years was injured in the blast.

On Sunday, March 1, we remembered 50-year-old John C. Moss III who was a civilian employee in the Army recruiting office where he served as chief of public affairs.

“He was very good at his job; he had found his niche. And he was very happy in Oklahoma City,” his sister, Marjorie Moss Hendrix, said.

On Monday, March 2, we remembered 31-year-old Ronota Ann Newberry-Woodbridge who was a pavement materials engineer with the Federal Highway Administration.

She and her husband, Gary, had been married eight years and were members of Edmond Church of Christ. Woodbridge was a graduate of Abilene Christian University.

On Tuesday, March 3, we remembered Patricia Ann Nix who worked for the Department of Housing and Urban Development for 21 years.

She and her husband Steve also started an antique business they called "Back in Time." Steve specialized in pocket watches; Patricia in furniture.

On Wednesday, March 4, we remembered 45-year-old Jerry Lee Parker who was a civil engineer with the Federal Highway Administration and a Sunday school teacher and trustee board member at Pleasant Hill Free Will Baptist Church.

He loved woodworking, collecting antiques, camping, and fishing. He especially loved to spend time outdoors with his family.

On Thursday, March 5, we remembered 27-year-old Jill Diane Randolph who was an accountant in the Federal Employees Credit Union since Dec. 1993.

Randolph was also committed to her church, where she was active in the Singles Twenties Group and the Bible Study Fellowship.

On Friday, March 6, we remembered 33-year-old Michelle A. Reeder who was was an administrative assistant with the Federal Highway Administration.

She was married to a Marine, Patrick Reeder, and was working to put him through college as he studied to be a history teacher.

On Saturday, March 7, we remembered 41-year-old Terry Smith Rees. Teddy bears were collectibles for Terry S. Rees, 41. Rees loved to travel to teddy bear and crafts shows, friends and family members said. She was the supervisor of public housing for the Department of Housing and Urban Development. Rees was married to Bob Chumard.

On Sunday, March 8, we remembered 55-year-old Antonio "Tony" C. Reyes who was an equal opportunity specialist for the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

The retired Navy senior chief petty officer was working on the eighth floor.

Dora Reyes remembers her husband as a “very generous, very outgoing, very friendly” person.

On Monday, March 9, we remembered 24-year-old Kathryn Elizabeth Ridley. In order to better herself for her two daughters, ages 4 years and 4 months, Kathryn was enrolled as a student at Guthrie Job Corps. Jacqueline Ridley said her sister-in-law had been on maternity leave from the Job Corps and had gone to the Job Corps recruiting office near the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building on the day of the explosion.

The young woman loved to write and was a very good artist. Sadly, most of her sketches were with her when she was killed, Jacqueline Ridley said. Jacqueline Ridley said her sister-in-law was taking welding classes at Job Corps, in the hopes that this training would help with her artistry. Kathryn was always smiling and loved to laugh. The sound of her laughter is what the family will miss most, Jacqueline Ridley said.


On Tuesday, March 10, we remembered 31-year-old Trudy Jean Rigney who was serving an internship as an assistant with the Oklahoma Water Resources Board when the blast hit.

Rigney was a senior studying geography at the University of Oklahoma.

On Wednesday, March 11, we remembered 48-year-old Claudine Ritter who was a collection officer for the Federal Employees Credit Union since Feb. 1987.

“Claudine Ritter had friends around the United States and was always helping others,” her cousin, Marilyn Harrington said.

On Thursday, March 12, we remembered 22-year-old Christy Rosas who had only worked five full days as a receptionist at the Federal Employees Credit Union before the explosion.

She was the “kind of person who always wanted to give to others before getting anything for herself” is the way her husband, Chris Rosas, described her.

On Friday, March 13, we remembered 27-year-old Sonja Sanders who loved her job at the Federal Employees Credit Union, where she worked for six years and had recently received a promotion.

Sanders was attending college and working toward a degree in banking and business.

On Saturday, March 14, we remembered 46-year-old Lanny Lee David Scroggins who had been a federal employee for 23 years, serving with several agencies in various accounting and financial management positions.

Coaching and playing ball with his two boys topped Scroggins’ list of favorite activities, followed by fishing.

Scroggins’ wife, Cheryl, described him as a wonderful, multifaceted person who loved music of all kinds and many outdoor activities.

On Sunday, March 15, we remembered 39-year-old Kathy Lynn Seidl who was an investigative assistant for the Secret Service.

Relatives described Kathy Lynn Seidl this way: A gracious and caring wife. A beautiful mother. A precious and loyal daughter. A dear sister. A special aunt.

On Monday, March 16, we remembered 58-year-old Leora Lee Sells who was a legal secretary for Housing and Urban Development.

She was also a Sunday school teacher and at one time had been a youth counselor for her church.

On Tuesday, March 17, we remembered 27-year-old Karan Howell Shepherd who was one of the favorite loan officers in the Federal Employees Credit Union.

She was even able to save a first-time car buyer $3,000.

On Wednesday, March 18, we remembered 3-year-old Chase Dalton Smith who had just been dropped off at the America's Kids day-care center at the Federal Building with his brother.

Brothers Colton Wade Smith and Chase Dalton Smith wanted to be together all the time, said their mother, Edye Smith. “They loved each other. They didn’t want to go anywhere without the other,” she said.

On Thursday, March 19, we remembered 2-year-old Colton Wade Smith who had just been dropped off at the America's Kids day-care center with his brother.

“They loved each other. They didn’t want to go anywhere without the other,” their mother, Edye Smith said.

On Friday, March 20, we remembered 36-year-old Master Sgt. Victoria Lee Sohn who gave 16 years to the service of her country.

“Placing all others’ needs above her own, she unselfishly gave her care and concern to all whose lives she touched,” read the obituary for Master Sgt. Sohn.

For Saturday, March 21, we remember 51-year-old John T. Stewart who was employed by the Department of Housing and Urban Development and worked 27 years for the government.

His brother, E.H. Stewart, described him as easygoing. “He minded his own business, looked after his own family,” Stewart said.

For Sunday, March 22, we remember 51-year-old Dolores M. Stratton who was a military personnel clerk for the Army recruiting office.

She was a good friend, mother and grandmother. Her husband was retired Air Force Master Sgt. Charles “Chuck” H. Stratton.

On Monday, March 23, we remembered 50-year-old Emilio Rangel Tapia who was a customer at the Social Security office.

Tapia attended the Tabernacle of Faith Church.

On Tuesday, March 24, we remembered 37-year-old Victoria J. Texter who was the VISA coordinator and a backup computer operator at the Federal Employees Credit Union.

Texter enjoyed making porcelain dolls and growing perennial flowers in her garden.

On Wednesday, March 25, we remembered 43-year-old Charlotte Andrea Lewis Thomas who had worked for the federal government for 17 years.

For the previous three years, Thomas had produced the Black Awareness program for the Social Security office.

On Thursday, March 26, we remembered 47-year-old Michael George Thompson who was a Vietnam veteran and was an employee of the Social Security Administration.

Thompson was a quiet man deeply devoted to his family.

On Friday, March 27, we remembered 56-year-old Virginia M. Thompson who had been employed by the Federal Employees Credit Union since January.

She was also the mother of two sons and a daughter – Ken, Phil and Shelly.

Phil said. Ken recalled his mother as “the most giving person I’ve ever met in my life,” and Phil said his mother was a “phenomenal woman, one who could literally almost do anything.”

On Saturday, March 28, we remembered 3-year-old Kayla Marie Titsworth who was at the Murrah Building with her family in the Army's recruiting office when the bomb exploded.

"She was always the first one there when you needed a hug and kiss."

On Sunday, March 29, we remembered 46-year-old Rick L. Tomlin who was a U.S. Department of Transportation motor vehicle safety officer.

Tomlin was remembered by family as a good father and a man who hated violence.


On Monday, March 30, we remembered 56-year-old LaRue A. Treanor. LaRue and Luther Treanor of Guthrie were married on June 28, 1959. LaRue loved to sing in the Seward Road Baptist Church choir, and Luther Treanor, 61, had a habit of tapping on pastor Rex Haymaker’s office window each Sunday on his way from the parking lot to the church.

The Treanors and their granddaughter Ashley Eckles, aged 4 at the time, went to the federal building for Luther’s appointment to check on his Social Security retirement. The Treanors had four children, Mike, Mark and Brad Treanor, and Debbie Price.

On Tuesday, March 31, we remembered 61-year- old Luther H. Treanor. LaRue and Luther Treanor of Guthrie were married on June 28, 1959. Luther Treanor had a habit of tapping on pastor Rex Haymaker’s office window each Sunday on his way from the parking lot to the church.

The Treanors and their granddaughter Ashley Eckles, aged 4 at the time, went to the federal building for Luther’s appointment to check on his Social Security retirement. The Treanors had four children, Mike, Mark and Brad Treanor, and Debbie Price.

On Wednesday, April 1, we remembered 43-year-old Larry L. Turner who was a special agent with the Department of Defense Investigative Services.

Turner also played clarinet in the St. John baptist Church orchestra. Music was his “first love,” according to those who knew him best.

On Thursday, April 2, we remembered 51-year-old Jules A. Valdez who worked in the Indian Affairs division of the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

“He was always willing to work, always willing to put forth an extra effort.” That’s how a fellow Rotarian described Jules Valdez.

On Friday, April 3, we remembered 67-year-old John Karl Van Ess III who was about to retire from his longtime job at the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

He is survived by his wife, four children and four grandchildren.

On Saturday, April 4, we remembered Johnny Allen Wade. He was a very optimistic person, one of those people who believed that whatever the problem, there was a solution. So he would say there’s no point spending time feeling sorry, said his wife, Joannie.

Johnny Allen Wade was the happiest when he was spending time with his family, especially his two children – Carla, who was 21 and a junior at the University of Oklahoma at the time; and Jerrel, who was 17 and a senior at Edmond Memorial High School. His second favorite pastime was fishing. Wade was an engineer for the Federal Highway Administration. He had gone to work for the government after getting a bachelor’s degree in engineering from Prairie View A&M University in Prairie View, Texas, in 1975. He and his family moved here from Little Rock, AR, in December 1991.

For Sunday, April 5, we remember 54-year-old David Jack Walker who was the environmental specialist with Housing and Urban Development.

“He was a wonderful father,” Janet Walker said of her husband. “He loved his three girls more than any father could. He never hung up the phone without saying, ‘I love you.’”

On Monday, April 6, we remembered 52-year-old Robert N. Walker Jr. Neither a heart attack suffered the year before nor the loss of his father could slow Robert Walker Jr. “He never slowed down,” said his wife, Judith Walker. “He was just so active, and he was really a wonderful man. I just wish everybody had had the chance to meet him.” Walker was a claims representative with the Social Security Administration, and his caring nature made a lasting impression on those he served, she said.

The Walkers had been married for almost nine years, and both worked for the Social Security Administration. They were transferred to Oklahoma City from Albuquerque, NM, three years ago. It was a good fit, Judith Walker said. “We were in love with Oklahoma City.” Walker continued his long association with the Boy Scouts in Oklahoma City. An Eagle Scout and 46-year member of the organization, Walker served as Assistant District Commissioner of the Will Rogers District and Unit Commissioner for Troop 84. Walker also pursued an avid interest in computers.

On Tuesday, April 7, we remembered 49-year-old Wanda Lee Watkins. Watkins was from Oklahoma City and could crochet circles around most people. She was a civilian who worked for the Army as a clerk in the recruiting office. Watkins loved to dance, was an Elvis fan and collected records and liquor bottles, although she didn’t drink. She also will be remembered for her good sense of humor and the colorful flowers in her garden.

On Wednesday, April 8, we remembered 45-year-old Michael D. Weaver who served as general counsel for the Department of Housing and Urban Development.

Weaver’s laughter, dry sense of humor and role of the “straight man” will always be remembered by his family.

On Thursday, April 9, we remembered 23-year-old Julie Marie Welch who has been working as a Spanish interpreter for the Social Security Administration.

Her goal was to be a Spanish teacher to help improve global understanding.

For Friday, April 10, we remember 57-year-old Robert G. Westberry who was only two years away from retiring as the special agent in charge at the Department of Defense and Investigative Services.

He loved to work on his computer and was dedicated to his family.

On Saturday, April 11, we remembered 40-year-old Alan G. Whicher who was the assistant special agent in charge at the U.S. Secret Service Oklahoma City field office.

Twenty minutes before the explosion on April 19, 1995, Alan Whicher phoned his wife, Pam, at home to give her a pep talk and wish her good luck before she gave a speech that day at a women’s Bible study at Oklahoma City University.

For Sunday, April 12, we remember 35-year-old Jo Ann Whittenberg who was known for the Italian cream and 7-Up pound cakes that she took to work and bake sales.

She was a program assistant at Housing and Urban Development.

On Monday, April 13, we remembered 48-year-old Frances Williams. She worked as a secretary with Housing and Urban Development for eight years. “She was an excellent mom and grandmother,” said her daughter, Dawn Mahan. She said her mother was an active member at her church, Crossroads Cathedral.

Mahan said that her mother’s favorite pastimes included playing with her three grandchildren and eating sweets, especially cake. “I love her and will always miss her,” Mahan added. “We will reunite one day.” Williams is survived by a brother, two children and three grandchildren. Her mother is Mozelle Bibb.

On Tuesday, April 14, we remembered 24-year-old Scott D. Williams. Williams would have been a new father in about two months. His wife, Nikki Williams, was expecting their first child, a girl they already had decided to name Kylie. “He was a wonderful person,” said his aunt, Linda Lekawski. Williams, a salesman for William E. Davis and Sons Food Inc., was making a delivery to the childcare center at the federal building.

On Wednesday, April 15, we remembered 42-year-old William Stephen Williams who was an operations supervisor for the Social Security Administration.

Williams’ best friend, Warren Vieth, a news editor for the Los Angeles Times’ Washington Bureau, wrote that he remembered the two forming a garage band during their teenage years.

For Thursday, April 16, we remember 53-year-old Clarence Eugene Wilson Sr. who was chief legal counsel for Housing and Urban Development.

His sister-in-law said he was a caring person who helped everybody.

For Friday, April 17, we remember 47-year-old Sharon Louise Wood-Chesnut. She was one of those people friends knew they could turn to during times of difficulty. An Oklahoma City native, she grew up in the Del City area and obtained a business degree before moving to Louisiana. She later returned to her hometown to work in the Social Security office, where she was known as a friendly, cheerful person who worked well with people.

She was a member of Christ Lutheran Church, where she served in several capacities, particularly those which required a good worker, planner or director. Wood-Chesnut had a daughter, Nikki Chesnut, and two stepchildren, Lonny Chesnut of Lafayette, LA, and Laurie O’Field of Houston, Texas.

For April 18, we remember 28-year-old Tresia Jo Worton. Personality – Tresia had it and shared it. “She was a real fun girl. She had a wonderful personality. She just bubbled,” said Florence Rogers, chief executive officer of the Federal Employees Credit Union, where Worton was a teller at the time of the bombing.

Rogers, a survivor of the blast, remembers that peppy personality being primary in Worton’s hiring last October. “She was so persistent. She kept calling and calling us for a job, and finally, we took a chance on her. And she was perfect. She was very proud of her job.” Worton, who was single and lived in Oklahoma City with her adopted Lhasa Apso, was buried in Midland, Texas, where her parents resided.

For April 19, we remember 52-year-old John A. Youngblood. John Albert “Buddy” Youngblood and his wife, Kathy, met in the emergency room at a New Mexico hospital where she worked and he, a state policeman, brought in an injured person for treatment. “It was probably love at first sight,” Kathy Youngblood said. The two had just celebrated their 21st anniversary that January. On Friday, Youngblood of Yukon, became the 168th person to die as a result of the April 19 explosion at the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
